# React Hook Form Patterns

When using **react-hook-form** in this project, follow these patterns.

## useWatch over watch()

`watch()` causes re-renders on every form change. Prefer `useWatch` for surgical updates.

```typescript
// ❌ Avoid — re-renders entire component on any field change
const allValues = methods.watch();
const singleValue = watch('fieldName');

// ✅ Prefer — surgical re-renders
import { useWatch } from 'react-hook-form';

const value = useWatch({ name: 'fieldName', control });

const [field1, field2] = useWatch({
  name: ['fieldName1', 'fieldName2'],
  control,
});
```

## Memoize Validation Schemas

Schemas are objects; recreating them every render triggers unnecessary validation.

```typescript
// ❌ Schema recreated every render
const schema = yup.object({ email: yup.string().email().required() });

// ✅ Memoized
const schema = useMemo(
  () => yup.object({ email: yup.string().email().required() }),
  []
);

// ✅ Or define outside component if no dependencies
const schema = yup.object({ email: yup.string().email().required() });
```

## FormProvider When Using Context

If child components need `useFormContext`, wrap the form in `FormProvider`:

```tsx
import { useForm, FormProvider } from 'react-hook-form';

const MyForm = () => {
  const methods = useForm({ defaultValues: { field: '' } });

  return (
    <FormProvider {...methods}>
      <form onSubmit={methods.handleSubmit(onSubmit)}>
        <input {...methods.register('field')} />
      </form>
    </FormProvider>
  );
};
```

## Form Inputs and A11y

All inputs must have associated labels (see a11y-standards.mdc). Use project `Input` with `label` prop or explicit `<label htmlFor="...">` + `id`.
